<h2>Overview</h2>
<p>
  <strong>Carousel</strong> presents a set of <em>equivalent slides</em> one (or a few) at a time, advanced
  by controls, pagination markers, swipe, or optional autoplay. It is for peer content the user browses
  (promos, images, cards) — distinct from <a href="/blocks/tabs/">tabs</a> (distinctly-labelled panels) and
  from paginated data (the <a href="/intents/collection-operations/">Collection Operations</a> intent).
</p>
<p>
  Native-first by construction: the substrate is a <strong>CSS scroll-snap container</strong>, and where
  supported the emerging <strong>CSS carousel pseudo-elements</strong> provide native prev/next and dot
  markers — so the block leans on the platform rather than re-implementing scroll logic in JavaScript.
</p>

<h2>Web Standards Alignment</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Standard</th><th>Status</th><th>How We Adopt It</th></tr>
  <tr><td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/docs/Web/CSS/CSS_scroll_snap">CSS Scroll Snap</a> (<code>scroll-snap-type</code> / <code>scroll-snap-align</code>)</td><td>Baseline 2024</td><td>The substrate — paging, momentum, touch, and arrow-key scrolling for free. The block defaults to it.</td></tr>
  <tr><td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/docs/Web/CSS/::scroll-button">::scroll-button()</a> / <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/docs/Web/CSS/::scroll-marker">::scroll-marker</a> (CSS Overflow 5)</td><td>Emerging (Open UI / CSS WG)</td><td>Native prev/next buttons and pagination dots where shipped — used instead of JS handlers; JS paging is the fallback only.</td></tr>
  <tr><td><a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/carousel/">WAI-ARIA APG Carousel</a></td><td>WAI-ARIA 1.2</td><td>Rotation announced via a live region; prev/next + slide-picker controls; slides as a named group. Baked in, not optional.</td></tr>
